details.description:
Anatolia Cafe & Cuisine
Get ready to experience the rich flavors of the Mediterranean! Anatolia Cafe & Cuisine brings you authentic Turkish and Mediterranean dishes, from savory kebabs to freshly baked pastries, paired with aromatic coffee and teas. We use only the finest ingredients to create a warm, inviting dining experience.

📍 1520 Overland Park Dr. Suite 107, Charlotte, NC 28262
We can’t wait to welcome you! Stay tuned for our grand opening and follow us for updates.

🍽️ Authentic Mediterranean & Turkish Cuisine

reviews_data.review_text: This is the best Turkish restaurant in Charlotte! I really enjoyed my experience — the food was amazing, and (( Raghad )) provided excellent customer service

We have tried Adana Kabab, the burger, lentil soup and Tiramisu cake and they all taste great.
Thank you Raghad for suggesting the best dishes!

New restaurant between UNC Charlotte and North Lake mall. Good menu options (plus breakfast too.) I had chicken sish kebab plate which was good. Quite similar to those you get in Turkiye. Not too spicy, cooked well, comes on a half pita and rice, and greens plus garlic yogurt sauce (I lightly dip the chicken pieces in it.) Lemon wedge for the greens and onions with sumac on them. Afetr lunch, the Turkish coffee was suberp. Like the desert options, to be tried the next time after a lighter lunch.

reviews_data.review_text:
The music was extremely loud, and despite our request to lower the volume due to our 3-month-old baby, the staff did not accommodate us.

As for the food, I ordered the **chicken shish kebab**, which was delicious. However, my husband had the **Adana kebab**, which was disappointing—while the flavor was similar to the authentic version, the meat was overly dry.

Since the restaurant owner is Turkish, we initially assumed the meat was **halal**. My husband asked the owner for confirmation, but they did not provide any legal halal certification or disclose their meat supplier. The only response we received was, *"You can be sure the meat is halal."* We hope that next time, they can present proper halal certification so we can dine with complete peace of mind.

I had the chance to try Anatolia twice — once for dinner and once for breakfast. During dinner, the waiter forgot to bring many items to the table, and we had to remind them several times. Most of the things we asked for were unavailable. Our salads were very poor. Despite this, I decided to give their breakfast a try because I had heard good things about their börek. Unfortunately, they were out of börek as well. I would recommend working on your presentation — you could even get help online. When a place presents itself as a Turkish restaurant and names itself “Anatolia,” people naturally expect the famous Turkish breakfast experience, but sadly, that’s not what we encountered.
Delicious food, friendly staff, and a warm, inviting atmosphere. Highly recommend!
This breakfast toast was amazing! I defiantly recommend it.

Julian is the kind of manager every business wishes they had. His commitment to customer satisfaction is unmatched — he genuinely cares about the guest experience and makes it his mission to ensure every detail meets the highest standard.

From the way he communicates to how he takes ownership of situations, Julian displays a level of professionalism and dedication that’s rare to find. He doesn’t just “do his job” — he leads with integrity, listens with empathy, and acts with purpose. You can clearly see that quality and customer happiness are his top priorities.

If more places had a leader like Julian, the entire service industry would be better for it. Truly outstanding!
Greek salad was amazing, great proportions and very fresh! The service and atmosphere here is very peaceful, I appreciate it and will definitely be coming back.
My favorite place ever! The service and food is amazing! The chef is so talented!

Just discovered Anatolia Cafe and Cuisine, and I have to say—it’s a welcome and refreshing addition to the local dining scene. From the moment you walk in, you’re greeted with warm hospitality and the inviting aroma of spices that instantly transport you to the Mediterranean.

The menu is thoughtfully curated with authentic Turkish and broader Mediterranean flavors. I tried the Adana kebab and it was perfectly spiced, juicy, and served with fluffy rice and fresh salad.

What really stood out was the attention to detail in presentation and service. The staff were knowledgeable and genuinely passionate about the cuisine. The decor also deserves a shoutout: modern, cozy, and tastefully accented with Anatolian touches.

I’ll definitely be back to explore more of the menu—especially the desserts (I’ve heard the baklava is phenomenal).

Highly recommend supporting this new local spot!

Anatolia was an amazing find! The place is spotless, modern, and very stylish. The food was delicious—especially the lahmacun and the freshly baked pastries. Great taste and great ambiance all in one! Hope you keep this level of quality and continue just like this! Thank you!

After being told we needed to have a reservation to eat dinner here we were excited to try.  We arrive and the guy ignored us,  the next staff ignored us... no one knew what was going on.  Dirty tables,  empty tables.. definitely didn't need a reservation.
Took them 15 minutes to acknowledge us,  no menus no anything.  The pastry cabinet was more than 3/4 empty.   Then they proceeded to tell us they're out of most of the menu,  especially the main dishes you would order when eating turkish food.  Sad to say after waiting all day to eat here and then driving 25 minutes..we didn't.

We visited Anatolia twice in our visit to Charlotte. The staff handled our big party with grace and efficiency, making everyone feel welcome and well taken care of.

reviews_data.review_text:
The recently opened Anatolia Cafe and Cuisine in Charlotte was great for the most part. We visited on an early Thursday evening for dinner and it wasn’t busy.

The lady serving us was quite polite and cheerful, which we really appreciated. For food, we got:

Mediterranean Mezze platter: The bread was delectable. Hummus, Babaganoush and tzatziki went well with the bread.

Garlic Parmesan Fries: These were okay. We were looking for more garlic and Parmesan, but the fries lacked them.

Chicken Pide: We were really looking forward to this but sadly it turned out to be quite bland. :(

The vanilla latte was great. They’ve an extensive menu consisting of pastries, teas and other food items from Turkish cuisine.

The seating area inside is large enough to accommodate busy hours.

Parking is available outside.

Overall it was a 3.5-4/5 star experience here.
reviews_data.owner_answer: Hi Akshat, thank you for taking time to leave your thorough feedback. We will take them into consideration. We are glad you liked our latte! We hope you come back again to try more drinks and dishes on the menu.

The music was extremely loud, and despite our request to lower the volume due to our 3-month-old baby, the staff did not accommodate us.

As for the food, I ordered the **chicken shish kebab**, which was delicious. However, my husband had the **Adana kebab**, which was disappointing—while the flavor was similar to the authentic version, the meat was overly dry.

Since the restaurant owner is Turkish, we initially assumed the meat was **halal**. My husband asked the owner for confirmation, but they did not provide any legal halal certification or disclose their meat supplier. The only response we received was, *"You can be sure the meat is halal."* We hope that next time, they can present proper halal certification so we can dine with complete peace of mind.

I had the chance to try Anatolia twice — once for dinner and once for breakfast. During dinner, the waiter forgot to bring many items to the table, and we had to remind them several times. Most of the things we asked for were unavailable. Our salads were very poor. Despite this, I decided to give their breakfast a try because I had heard good things about their börek. Unfortunately, they were out of börek as well. I would recommend working on your presentation — you could even get help online. When a place presents itself as a Turkish restaurant and names itself “Anatolia,” people naturally expect the famous Turkish breakfast experience, but sadly, that’s not what we encountered.

Julian is the kind of manager every business wishes they had. His commitment to customer satisfaction is unmatched — he genuinely cares about the guest experience and makes it his mission to ensure every detail meets the highest standard.

From the way he communicates to how he takes ownership of situations, Julian displays a level of professionalism and dedication that’s rare to find. He doesn’t just “do his job” — he leads with integrity, listens with empathy, and acts with purpose. You can clearly see that quality and customer happiness are his top priorities.

Just discovered Anatolia Cafe and Cuisine, and I have to say—it’s a welcome and refreshing addition to the local dining scene. From the moment you walk in, you’re greeted with warm hospitality and the inviting aroma of spices that instantly transport you to the Mediterranean.

The menu is thoughtfully curated with authentic Turkish and broader Mediterranean flavors. I tried the Adana kebab and it was perfectly spiced, juicy, and served with fluffy rice and fresh salad.

What really stood out was the attention to detail in presentation and service. The staff were knowledgeable and genuinely passionate about the cuisine. The decor also deserves a shoutout: modern, cozy, and tastefully accented with Anatolian touches.

I’ll definitely be back to explore more of the menu—especially the desserts (I’ve heard the baklava is phenomenal).

Highly recommend supporting this new local spot!

The recently opened Anatolia Cafe and Cuisine in Charlotte was great for the most part. We visited on an early Thursday evening for dinner and it wasn’t busy.

The lady serving us was quite polite and cheerful, which we really appreciated. For food, we got:

Mediterranean Mezze platter: The bread was delectable. Hummus, Babaganoush and tzatziki went well with the bread.

Garlic Parmesan Fries: These were okay. We were looking for more garlic and Parmesan, but the fries lacked them.

Chicken Pide: We were really looking forward to this but sadly it turned out to be quite bland. :(

The vanilla latte was great. They’ve an extensive menu consisting of pastries, teas and other food items from Turkish cuisine.

The seating area inside is large enough to accommodate busy hours.

Parking is available outside.

Overall it was a 3.5-4/5 star experience here.

Anatolia Cafe & Cuisine
Get ready to experience the rich flavors of the Mediterranean! Anatolia Cafe & Cuisine brings you authentic Turkish and Mediterranean dishes, from savory kebabs to freshly baked pastries, paired with aromatic coffee and teas. We use only the finest ingredients to create a warm, inviting dining experience.

📍 1520 Overland Park Dr. Suite 107, Charlotte, NC 28262
We can’t wait to welcome you! Stay tuned for our grand opening and follow us for updates.
